    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2195629553" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2195629553" />
    <a title="J" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/869064-j"><img alt="J" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1623941810p2/869064.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2195629553?book_show_action=true">Nov 26, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="J" class="user" itemprop="url" name="J" href="/user/show/869064-j">J</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/869064-j?shelf=japanese-literature">japanese-literature</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2195629553" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9703214611355934027">This is an earlier and much more auto-biographical book than the other Mishima I&apos;ve read, and you can see here the themes that obsessed him so much in almost all of his later writing: the conflicts with his sexuality, his all-consuming obsession with dying and death, his sense of himself as a deformed outsider, &apos;hiding&apos; in plain site.<br/><br/>Reading this as a gay guy who was in almost total denial about his sexuality into his mid 20&apos;s, there are parts of this that, even across generations and intense cu</span>
  <span id="freeText9703214611355934027" style="display:none">This is an earlier and much more auto-biographical book than the other Mishima I've read, and you can see here the themes that obsessed him so much in almost all of his later writing: the conflicts with his sexuality, his all-consuming obsession with dying and death, his sense of himself as a deformed outsider, 'hiding' in plain site.<br /><br />Reading this as a gay guy who was in almost total denial about his sexuality into his mid 20's, there are parts of this that, even across generations and intense cultural divides, will feel brutally true to the lives of many young LGBT people, even in 2017. He brilliantly articulates the fundamental loneliness, and the senses of perpetual denial and fear that, alas, are an integral part of so much of queer experience. Parts of this almost made me cringe when I think of just how well they applied to my teenage self.<br /><br />Personal reflections aside, this is pretty down-to-earth by Mishima standards, but even a Mishima novel that isn't totally crazed with wounded self-loathing, and multi-page descriptions of erotic/artistic obsession and mania is still a very solid novel. This is a good place to start if you've never read him before.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9703214611355934027" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


