    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1580220484" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1580220484" />
    <a title="Cody" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/48027559-cody"><img alt="Cody" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1507665393p2/48027559.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1580220484?book_show_action=true">Mar 15, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Cody" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Cody" href="/user/show/48027559-cody">Cody</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/787423.Confessions_of_a_Mask">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/48027559-cody?shelf=japanese-lit">japanese-lit</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1580220484" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8590609724918508">What we have here is a classic Japanese ‘I’ novel that has been taken as autobiography and gospel by Mishima fetishists. As with Vollmann, it seems like readers want to hang their heroic (or anti-heroic) baggage around the author’s neck and praise or damn him for the actions of his characters. Big mistake. As with WTV, we must assume that Mishima’s <i>Mask</i> begins from a place of truth and fictionalizes from there. As the facts of his clandestine actions rolled off his hunky shoulders along with his</span>
  <span id="freeText8590609724918508" style="display:none">What we have here is a classic Japanese ‘I’ novel that has been taken as autobiography and gospel by Mishima fetishists. As with Vollmann, it seems like readers want to hang their heroic (or anti-heroic) baggage around the author’s neck and praise or damn him for the actions of his characters. Big mistake. As with WTV, we must assume that Mishima’s <i>Mask</i> begins from a place of truth and fictionalizes from there. As the facts of his clandestine actions rolled off his hunky shoulders along with his head when he idiotically committed <i>seppuku</i>, the truth is that we will never really know. Why his 'degree' of homosexuality so fascinates his fans is ever a mystery to me. <br /><br />Published in 1949, this is wildly ahead of its time in terms of frankness of subject matter and, as such, gets filed away in that big box with “Important Shit” written on it. The story of a homosexual man’s journey from (possibly) literal childbirth through his early-twenties, we witness our narrator's slow-dawning realization that he is, in the words of warrior-poet Ray Davies (Clan Kinks), not like everybody else. <br /><br />So why three stars? The middle act just sags (unlike Mishima’s prodigious musculature). The First Act, when our hero begins to understand his sexual proclivity toward other boys, is just agonizing, brutal stuff. The Third Act redeems a lot of the overlong middle. But Chapter Two seems a slog in its attempt to pad out to novel length. <br /><br />From the first chapter: <br /><br />“<i>When a boy of fourteen or fifteen discovers that he is more given to introspection and consciousness of self than other boys his age, he easily falls into the error of believing it is because he is more mature than they. This was certainly a mistake in my case. Rather it was because the other boys had no such need of understanding themselves as I had: they could be their natural selves, whereas I was to play a part, a fact that would require considerable understanding and study. So it was not my maturity but my sense of uneasiness, my uncertainty, that was forcing me to gain control over my consciousness.</i>”<br /><br />or: <br /><br />"<i>For over a year now I had been suffering the anguish of a child provided with a curious toy. I was twelve years old.<br />This toy increased in volume at every opportunity and hinted that, rightly used, it would be quite a delightful thing. But directions for its use were nowhere written, and so, when the toy took the initiative in wanting to play with me, my bewilderment was inevitable. Occasionally my humiliation and impatience became so aggravated that I even thought I wanted to destroy the toy. In the end, however, there was nothing for it but to surrender on my side to the insubordinate toy, with its expression of sweet secrecy, and wait passively to see what would happen.<br />Then I took it into my head to try listening more dispassionately to the toy's wishes. When I did so, I found that soon it already possessed its own definite and unmistakable tastes, or what might be called its own mechanism. The nature of its tastes had become bound up, not only with my childhood memories, but, one after another, with such things as the naked bodies of young men seen on a summer's seashore, the swimming teams seen at Meiji Pool, the swarthy young man a cousin of mine married, and the valiant heroes of many an adventure story. Until then I had mistakenly thought I was only poetically attracted to such things, thus confusing the nature of my sensual desires with a system of esthetics.</i>”<br /><br />What I respect about Mishima, like Vollmann, is that neither allows himself to linger too long in self-pity. You won’t hear the term ‘sentimentalist’ thrown at either very often. As a gay man living during a different era under very different societal pressures, Mishima came out of the gate with a whipcrack in <i>Mask</i>. Still, it’s heartbreaking to read the following and think that, if it wasn’t Mishima’s exact mindset, I can only assume it may have been—and still may be—the reality that some young men face upon realizing they are gay:<br /><br />“<i>Suddenly I was struck by the astringent pain that comes from staring too long at something. The pain proclaimed: You're not human. You're a being who is incapable of social intercourse. You're nothing but a creature, non-human and somehow strangely pathetic.</i>”<br /><br />I hope I am wrong. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="8590609724918508" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


