        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2072421322" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7826878468782035279">Mishima&apos;s second novel is a dark, introspective meandering through the thoughts of a young man discovering his homosexuality. Problem is, coming out of the closet here means emerging into an even darker room lit only by occasional chopping lights shining through the eye slits of the demonic mask that forms the opposite wall.<br/>This isn&apos;t a light book. Mishima, who apparently struggled with his own homosexuality a la Proust, leads you through the harrowing thought processes of someone coming to term</span>
  <span id="freeText7826878468782035279" style="display:none">Mishima's second novel is a dark, introspective meandering through the thoughts of a young man discovering his homosexuality. Problem is, coming out of the closet here means emerging into an even darker room lit only by occasional chopping lights shining through the eye slits of the demonic mask that forms the opposite wall.<br />This isn't a light book. Mishima, who apparently struggled with his own homosexuality a la Proust, leads you through the harrowing thought processes of someone coming to terms with the lie of their life, the artificiality of their socially accepted heterosexuality and the torments within that ensue.</span>
