<div id="review_2343814676" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2343814676" />
    <a title="Inderjit Sanghera" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/900800-inderjit-sanghera"><img alt="Inderjit Sanghera" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1564826235p2/900800.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2343814676?book_show_action=true">Mar 29, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Inderjit Sanghera" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Inderjit Sanghera" href="/user/show/900800-inderjit-sanghera">Inderjit Sanghera</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2343814676" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7240553071969527218">Lugubrious, with a waft of decadence and death, ‘Confessions of Mask’ is Mishima’s most personal work, a paean to his morbid tendencies, to his neuroses, to the mask he wore which covered the elements of his personality which he wished to hide; his latent homosexuality and fascination with masculinity, his callous views on love, his self-absorption and macabre personality.<br/><br/>The novel follows the adolescence and early adulthood on a teenager who is clearly a stand-in for Mishima. The image of St. S</span>
  <span id="freeText7240553071969527218" style="display:none">Lugubrious, with a waft of decadence and death, ‘Confessions of Mask’ is Mishima’s most personal work, a paean to his morbid tendencies, to his neuroses, to the mask he wore which covered the elements of his personality which he wished to hide; his latent homosexuality and fascination with masculinity, his callous views on love, his self-absorption and macabre personality.<br /><br />The novel follows the adolescence and early adulthood on a teenager who is clearly a stand-in for Mishima. The image of St. Sebatian, naked and virile, haunts him and becomes a kind of benchmark for physical beauty, this manifests itself in his flirtations with the brash and vulgar young men in his school, who he secretly worships. Coalesced with all of this are his fascination with death, with his fantasies; being Mishima, ‘Confessions of a Mask is replete with fantastical imagery;<br /><br />“One night from my bed I see a city shining city floating upon the expanse of darkness that surrounded me. It was strangely still, and yet overflowed with brilliance and mastery. I could plainly see a mystic brand that had been impressed upon the faces of hte persons in that country.”<br /><br />The whole world is imbued with a kind of sinister fairy tale magic, Mishima’s dreams loom large over the world, which is transmogrified into a world of shadows and half-light, a world delirious with Mishima’s feverish fantasies, where an ejaculation resembles a cloud and the atmosphere takes on the two-dimensional, artificial quality of a Japanese miniature painting;<br /><br />“The great elm-like trees towered up with a plastic delicacy in the blue winter sky, in the reflection of the snow from below, in the lateral rays of the morning sin; and occasionally some snow slipped down like gold dust from the crotches formed against the tree trunk by the stark, leafless branches”<br /><br />Fecund with Misima’s febrile imagination, “Confessions of a Mask” is his most deeply personal work; from his relationship with his over-protective grandmother, to his sense of weakness which eventually manifested itself in his sense of violence, to his problematic relationships with women, to his constant societal transgressions which cause him to wear a mask which is only removed in his novels.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7240553071969527218" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

