<div id="review_432424793" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/432424793" />
    <a title="Chaitra" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9086236-chaitra"><img alt="Chaitra" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1432611617p2/9086236.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/432424793?book_show_action=true">Oct 11, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Chaitra" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Chaitra" href="/user/show/9086236-chaitra">Chaitra</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/787423.Confessions_of_a_Mask">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9086236-chaitra?shelf=japanese-literature">japanese-literature</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9086236-chaitra?shelf=child-or-teenage-protagonist">child-or-teenage-protagonist</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9086236-chaitra?shelf=literary-fiction">literary-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer432424793" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15178205449994119612">Unsatisfied by this. It was probably the wrong book to start Mishima with. The whiny central character talks about a mask he&apos;s been wearing ever since he can remember. Yet, he does nothing fruitful whatsoever, except for wishing that he was dead. Does he even try to find others like himself? He&apos;s 21 in 1945 in Japan, I cannot think that men preferring men were totally unheard of at that point. I could handle his guilt, his shame. What I couldn&apos;t handle was his douchiness (it should be word, if i</span>
  <span id="freeText15178205449994119612" style="display:none">Unsatisfied by this. It was probably the wrong book to start Mishima with. The whiny central character talks about a mask he's been wearing ever since he can remember. Yet, he does nothing fruitful whatsoever, except for wishing that he was dead. Does he even try to find others like himself? He's 21 in 1945 in Japan, I cannot think that men preferring men were totally unheard of at that point. I could handle his guilt, his shame. What I couldn't handle was his douchiness (it should be word, if it's not). At one point he convinces himself he's in love with an innocent girl of 18. He then jilts her because obviously he doesn't care for her sexually. Also, because he never thought that he might actually have to marry the girl, he was hoping a bomb would fall on him before that. Doesn't happen and the girl goes on to marry someone else. Then he suddenly thinks he might actually be in love with her again? After she's married he continues to meet her, respectably, supposedly. When she asks why they didn't marry, he has nothing to say to her except that hey, I was too young and you married while I was hesitating. <br /><br />I'm aware that being sexually different can be crippling, but this guy was a wanker. What pissed me off is that he continually thinks of life an experiment. One he can escape because he may die. Then he's surprised that he's not dead and he has to face consequences, and there's some other convenient out for him. The title is right, in a way, I never really got the feeling that I was reading about something genuine, that there was something to the guy I was reading about. I'm wondering if Mishima did a big disfavor to the gay community, I can't think that anyone might want to identify with this guy. He's morally skewed, he even admits it. He loves (it's all very poetic) young men from afar, his favorite twisted fantasy is of a naked man in the throes of bloody death. Is that not all the clichés of homosexuality come true?<br /><br />I recognize the craft, and the language. I just wish it was something better than this story of a mask.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15178205449994119612" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


